{{refimprove|date=April 2016}}

The '''Jerusalem Islamic Waqf''' is an [[Waqf|Islamic religious trust]] (sometimes called an "Islamic Religious Endowments" organization) best known for controlling and managing the current Islamic edifices on and around the [[Temple Mount]] in the [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old City of Jerusalem]], including the [[Al-Aqsa Mosque]] and the [[Dome of the Rock]].<ref name="AM20140905">{{cite news|title=Arab states neglect Al-Aqsa says head of Jerusalem Waqf|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/09/khatib-muslim-endowments-israel-jordan-al-aqsa.html|accessdate=5 April 2016|work=[[Al-Monitor]]|date=5 September 2014}}</ref> Some form or another of the waqf has governed access to the Haram esh-Sharif since the [[Saladin#Capture of Jerusalem|Muslim reconquest]] of the [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]] in 1187, with the latest version instituted by the [[Jordan|Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan]] after its conquest of the West Bank and East Jerusalem during the 1948 war.<ref name="books.google.be">{{cite book|last1=Sachar|first1=Howard M.|title=A History of Israel: From the Rise of Zionism to Our Time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0X4BAAAAQBAJ|edition=2|date=2013|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8041-5049-1|accessdate=2016-03-20}}</ref> Accordingly, the King of Jordan currently supplies all of the funding needed to operate the waqf, which is in effect the civil administration for the holy site.<ref name="AM20140905" />

[[Israel]] occupied the Old City of Jerusalem during the [[Six-Day War]] of June 1967. After the end of hostilities, Israel allowed the waqf to retain authority over the [[Temple Mount]] (Haram esh-Sharif).<ref name="MFA20141117">{{cite web|title=Behind the Headlines: Jerusalem's Temple Mount|url=http://mfa.gov.il/MFA/ForeignPolicy/Issues/Pages/Jerusalem-Temple-Mount-12-Nov-2014.aspx|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Israel)|Israel Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]|accessdate=5 April 2016|date=17 November 2014}}</ref>

The waqf administration is headed by a director (or sometimes "director-general") who runs the civil administration for the holy sites.<ref name="AM20140905" /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Reiter|first1=Yitzhak|title=Islamic Endowments in Jerusalem Under British Mandate|date=1996|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=0714643424|pages=272|edition=First|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SJOaAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> The [[Grand Mufti of Jerusalem]] is in charge of Islamic religious affairs at the site. The [[Supreme Muslim Council]] is the Islamic judicial body governing affairs under Islamic law within Israel. The [[Palestinian National Authority|Palestinian Authority]] has parallel organizations claiming interest in these same matters (i.e., the Ministry of Islamic Waqf at the Palestinian Authority,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Ministry of Islamic Waqf at the Palestinian Authority|url=http://www.crihl.org/content/ministry-islamic-waqf-palestinian-authority|website=The Council of the Religious Institutions of the Holy Land|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref> the Palestinian Authority Grand Mufti, or the Palestinian Supreme Fatwa Council<ref>{{cite web|title=PA Mufti and Islamic council: Israel plans to Judaize Jerusalem and Al-Aqsa Mosque|url=http://www.palwatch.org/main.aspx?fi=606&doc_id=15372|website=[[Palestinian Media Watch]]|publisher=[[Al-Hayat al-Jadida]]|accessdate=5 April 2016}}</ref>), and those are not to be confused with those recognized by Israel, even if some of the same people hold both offices.

