{{nihongo|'''Shinji Shūmeikai'''|神慈秀明会}} (often abbreviated to '''Shumei''') is a [[Japan]]ese [[new religious movement]] ([[Japanese new religions|shinshūkyō]]). In 1998, the organization had more than 300,000 adherents.<ref name="nyt-reif">{{cite news|last=Reif|first=Rita|title=ARTS/ARTIFACTS; A Japanese Vision of the Ancient World|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/08/16/arts/arts-artifacts-a-japanese-vision-of-the-ancient-world.html|accessdate=13 August 2010|newspaper=The New York Times|date=16 August 1998}}</ref>
== Beliefs == Shumei believes in the pursuit of beauty through art, appreciation of nature<ref>{{cite book|last=Rosenblatt|first=Arthur |title=Building type basics for museums|year=2001|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|isbn=0-471-34915-1|pages=32|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yTggWMQ42qQC&pg=PA32&dq=shinji+shumeikai&hl=en&ei=Q6BkTOj1N8P98QbMi8XsCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=shinji%20shumeikai&f=false}}</ref> and "natural agriculture", a method of food cultivation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shumei - Our Environment|url=http://www.shumei.org/environment/environment_01.html|publisher=Shinji Shumeikai|accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref> They also practice [[johrei]], a type of spiritual healing.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shumei - jyorei|url=http://www.shumei.org/jyorei/jyorei_00.html|publisher=Shinji Shumeikai|accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref> Adherents of Shumei believe that, in building architectural masterpieces in remote locations, they are restoring the Earth's balance.<ref>{{cite book|last=Sharlet|first=Jeff |title=The Family: power, politics and fundamentalism's shadow elite|year=2008|publisher=Univ. of Queensland Press|isbn=0-7022-3694-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NVmcx-8zdGEC&pg=PA56&dq=shinji+shumeikai&hl=en&ei=EKVkTMubJ9_z8QaD3tzrCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CD0Q6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=shinji%20shumeikai&f=false}}</ref>
== History == Shinji Shūmeikai was founded by [[Mihoko Koyama]] in 1970.<ref name="nyt-reif"/> She founded the organization to spread the teachings of [[Mokichi Okada]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Melikian |first=Souren |title=A Splendid Art Collection Goes On Display in Japan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/06/style/06iht-museum.t.html |accessdate=13 August 2010 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=6 November 1997 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140115085728/http://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/06/style/06iht-museum.t.html |archivedate=January 15, 2014 }}</ref>
The head organization is currently based near [[Shigaraki, Shiga|Shigaraki]], [[Shiga prefecture|Shiga]], Japan.
== Influence and architecture == The [[Miho Museum]] was commissioned by Mihoko Koyama, who was an adherent of Okada.<ref name="sfgate">{{cite news|last=Baker|first=Kenneth |title=Miho Lets Art Speak For Itself|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2007-11-18/entertainment/17270344_1_10th-anniversary-pedestrian-tunnel-objects|accessdate=13 August 2010|newspaper=San Francisco Gate|date=18 November 2007}}</ref> The architect [[I. M. Pei]] had earlier designed the bell tower at Misono,<ref>{{cite web|title=Shumei - Art and Beauty|url=http://www.shumei.org/artandbeauty/misono_tour.html}}</ref> the international headquarters and spiritual center of the Shumei organisation. Mihoko Koyama and her daughter, Hiroko Koyama, again commissioned Pei to design the Miho Museum. The bell tower can be seen from the windows of the museum.
Founders Hall was designed by Japanese-American architect [[Minoru Yamasaki]].<ref name="detnews_people">{{cite news |title=Minoru Yamasaki, world-class architect |publisher=The Detroit News |author=Vivian M. Baulch |date=August 14, 1998 |accessdate=2007-11-23 |url=http://info.detnews.com/redesign/history/story/historytemplate.cfm?id=206 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130102100346/http://info.detnews.com/redesign/history/story/historytemplate.cfm?id=206 |archivedate=January 2, 2013 |df= }}</ref>
