{{short description|Scientology metaphor used to describe advancement in the religion}}
'''The Bridge to Total Freedom''', or simply "The Bridge", is a metaphor used by the [[Church of Scientology]] to describe believers' advancement within the religion.

Scientology holds that believers advance to a state of [[Clear (Scientology)|Clear]] when they have freed themselves from the "[[reactive mind]]". This takes place in [[Auditing (Scientology)|auditing]], and is said to be a lifetime commitment.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ashcraft |first1=W. Michael |title=Introduction to New and Alternative Religions in America: African diaspora traditions and other American innovations |volume=5 |editor-last=Gallagher |editor-first=Eugene V. |editor2-last=Ashcraft |editor2-first=W. Michael |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2006 |isbn=9780275987176 }}</ref> According to the church, by reaching Clear status, followers are more self-confident, happy, and generally successful in careers and interpersonal relationships. Beyond the state of Clear, Scientologists move through several auditing steps called [[Operating Thetan]] (OT) levels. An OT is a state of spiritual awareness in which an individual is able to control self and the environment.<ref>{{cite news|last=Semuels|first=Alana|title=Bridge to Total Freedom a lifetime commitment|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/05205/542900.stm|accessdate=12 July 2011|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=24 July 2005}}</ref> According to D. R. Christensen, Scientology is "an individualistic religion with a hierarchical organization of the soteriological system, called the Bridge". The Bridge is described by the church as a series of [[Soteriology|soteriological]] steps.<ref>{{cite book |last=Christensen |first1= Dorthe Refslund |title=Scientology |chapter=Scientology and Self-Narrativity: Theology and Soteriology as Resource and Strategy |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=MtW90YkkB3gC&oi=fnd&pg=PA103&dq=scientology&ots=01Zxc5kCXm&sig=aXHPXYVcaOFg4E5ksN8hN17kzwE#v=onepage&q=scientology&f=false |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2009 |accessdate=2016-08-18 }}</ref>

The Bridge is broken down into two parallel paths, Training and Processing. Processing addresses the Scientologist's "case" or how they function in life as influenced by their "aberrations". The Training path teaches Hubbard's theories on the nature of life and the universe and the techniques of [[Auditing (Scientology)|auditing]]. Participants feel that this knowledge greatly enhances their ability to be effective in life whether they audit another or not.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}} Scientologists can travel up either side of the Bridge and many do both sides. Although not part of the formal Bridge, the chart also lists many optional courses and training actions that can be done by Scientologists.

The Bridge was a result of the culmination of the foundational work on Dianetics and Scientology training that Hubbard had established in the mid-1960s. In 1965, Hubbard published The Bridge to Freedom, which includes the “Classification and Gradation Chart,” which, according to [[new religious movement]] specialist [[James R. Lewis (scholar)|James R. Lewis]], discusses the steps that church members must follow as they learn and study Scientology. The chart was a summary of the results of Hubbard’s experimentation since the Hubbard Dianetics Research Foundation was founded fifteen years before that time. Save for adjustments and addendums over several years, it delineated the program for reaching Clear status and becoming an Operating Thetan.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewis |first1=James R. |url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=MtW90YkkB3gC&oi=fnd&pg=PR7&dq=scientology&ots=01Zxd9pKWk&sig=NHxEdB5pOVlMRVNX74Kl8UQnKI4#v=onepage&q=scientology&f=false |title=Scientology |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2009 |accessdate=2016-08-15 }}</ref>

Scientologists believe that if an individual is unable to ascend through the Bridge in this lifetime, he or she can continue the journey up the Bridge in another life.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Scientology: Religious Studies Approaches |journal=Numen |year=2016 |last=Lewis |first=James R. |volume=63 |issue=1 |pages=6–11 }}</ref>

